{"iteration":19,"action":{"reasoning":"Observation: Iteration 18's LSTM+attention model scored 0.7453 AUC, well below the best 0.7594 from iteration 6. Recent single-model experiments consistently plateau around 0.743-0.750 except for the isolated iteration 6 peak. Analysis: The core LSTM-DKT architecture with LayerNorm (no attention, no MLP, no packing) is still the most promising. A likely overlooked issue is that padded time-steps (skill=0, correct=0) pass through the embedding lookup just like real interactions, feeding misleading gradients into the LSTM. By zeroing-out embeddings at padded positions using sequence lengths, the LSTM receives cleaner inputs. This is a lightweight, principled fix that avoids the complexity/bugs of pack_padded_sequence. To exploit random-seed variance within our remaining budget (~14 min, 12 iters), I'll run three independent training runs in one iteration and keep the best validation model. Decision: Revert model.py to the simple 2-layer LSTM-DKT with LayerNorm, add optional embedding masking via lengths. Update train.py and predict.py to pass lengths. Train three models (seeds 0,1,2) sequentially with patience=7, pick the best via validation AUC, copy to best_model.pt, and submit eval.","command":"python train.py --seed 0 --patience 7 --save_path model_0.pt && python train.py --seed 1 --patience 7 --save_path model_1.pt && python train.py --seed 2 --patience 7 --save_path model_2.pt && python pick_best.py","submit_eval":{"checkpoint_path":"best_model.pt","predict_script":"predict.py"},"done":false,"files_written":["model.py","pick_best.py","predict.py","train.py"]},"command_output":{"exit_code":0,"timed_out":false,"elapsed_seconds":87.24975204467773,"stdout":"model_0.pt: val_auc=0.7450\nmodel_1.pt: val_auc=0.7465\nmodel_2.pt: val_auc=0.7455\nBest: model_1.pt (0.7465)\nCopied best model to best_model.pt\n","stderr":"2026-04-25 18:58:09,211 - INFO - Device: cuda, Seed: 0\n2026-04-25 18:58:14,302 - INFO - Epoch 1/50: train_loss=0.63